				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Warrior CC?<a name="54715"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 2 04 2:53 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Had a couple of interesting LDoN adventures lately, and I'd be grateful for some opinions on something that happened in one of them.  (Feel free to skip the next couple of paragraphs to get to the important bit!)
<br />

<br />
We had a pretty strong group, with a 60 cleric, 55 pally and warr, me at 54, a ~57 necro and a berzerker of roughly my level.  The pally is pulling, which is fine by me because I like a break from the non-stop madness of most adventures.
<br />

<br />
So, I'm playing mana all the time, also hasting and slowing, and chanting as circumstances permit.  Of course, I'm crowd control too but had no difficulties since the adventure was a Normal and everything was nice and blue to me.
<br />

<br />
THE IMPORTANT BIT:  
<br />

<br />
So, occasionally the pally brings back two or three (once, 4) and I jump into CC mode.  When I'm mezzing one, I'm quite happy also meleeing the other and slowing it, with haste too if things get settled, so I'm doing that.  The 55 warrior is the MA, and after a while asks me to stop mezzing single adds, because Song of Twilight pulls them around so much.
<br />

<br />
I'm a little confused at this stage, but whatever, that's fine by me as long as everyone else is happy.  The rest of the adventure proceeds as usual, and we finish in a decent if unspectacular time.  Afterwards I asked the pally what that was all about, and he tells me that a good warrior can tank two mobs at once on a Normal adventure.
<br />

<br />
Fine, I'm new to this end of the game and I'm prepared to believe that, but:
<br />

<br />
1) Surely the extra damage from the add is better mitigated by my mez than by any double-tanking warrior?  If the cleric needs to CH the MA, you know where that add is going...
<br />

<br />
2) Is there any situation where such back-alley, ghetto CC is important when you've got a bard or chanter who could easily mez the mob?
<br />

<br />
3) If you have a warrior in your group that thinks they can tank two and is clearly is NOT having much success in actually doing so, how the h*ll do you go about telling them that?
<br />

<br />
None of this would have made much difference to that adventure, but I know I've been in adventures where it could have been a big problem.  In this case, I get the impression that the pally was taking a bit of agro to spread the damage around, but we would have survived either way.
<br />

<br />
P.S. The other interesting adventure was with a full group that had a druid for a healer and and a sleepy tank with poor melee stats.  We went for a BB hard, 70% of mobs were yellow to me, and about 45 mins in the warrior went MIA -- fell asleep at the keyboard, we later discovered.  After a short argument on the relative importance of RL vs EQ, we still almost won, but the druid just couldn't keep up with the healing.  In the end, we got partial points in overtime.  It was my first loss, but at least it wasn't my fault! *grin*
<br />

<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
