				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Warrior CC?<a name="54734"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 2 04 8:17 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>If mana wasnt being an issue for the cleric, and the tank was actually able to hold aggro on both mobs, nothing wrong with their approach.
<br />

<br />
Twilight's push is both good and bad.  It helps to seperate mobs a little, making CC slightly easier, but if you only face in one direction the mobs eventually pushed into walls or OOR or right in the middle of the casters.
<br />

<br />
A decent solution since you are meleeing with the others anyway is simply to change your facing.  Twilight always pulls the mob away from the direction you are facing if I remember right.  So once the mob is past you and Twilight pulses, the mob is pushed away from your back.  After 5-6 pulses, just change side on the current tank mob.  Face the other way, and the mez CC'd mob will bounce towards you.
<br />

<br />
We did a kill 32 Guk run the other day... Warrior, Monk, Monk, Cleric, Bard, Necro all 65.  Normally we do Hard level so it's the usual pull, split, CC, etc.  This time we let the warrior pull freely and didnt bother with mez or even slow.  The cleric stuck to low aggro HoTime as much as possible.  I played Haste, Overhaste, and DS.  He'd pull anything from 7-10 mobs.  In 10-15 minutes we were done with the adventure and waiting on the timer for a new one.  The fact is, as you progress to 65+ the normal level mobs are incredibly easy.  Most bards could probably tank them, but we have no method to solidly hold aggro once nukes and heals start.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
